05216nam a22007815i 9781400827138DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2009    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008271387 a10.1515/97814008271382doi  a(DE-B1597)446448  a(OCoLC)979725974  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aREL1050002bisacsh04a261.800aAuthorizing Marriage? :bCanon, Tradition, and Critique in the Blessing of Same-Sex Unions /cMark D. Jordan.  aCourse Book 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2009] 4c©2006  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00t Frontmatter -- tContents -- tContributors -- tIntroduction / rJordan, Mark D. -- t"Surpassing The Love Of Women" / rOlyan, Saul M. -- tFamiliar Idolatry and the Christian Case against Marriage / rMartin, Dale B. -- tMarriage and Friendship in the Christian New Testament / rTolbert, Mary Ann -- tWhy Is Rabbi Yoḥanan a Woman? or, A Queer Marriage Gone Bad / rBoyarin, Daniel -- tCan I Really Count on You? / rHemming, Laurence Paul -- tContemplating a Jewish Ritual of Same-Sex Union / rGreenberg, Steven -- tArguing Liturgical Genealogies, or, The Ghosts of Weddings Past / rJordan, Mark D. -- tHooker and the New Puritans / rTanner, Kathryn -- tAd Imaginem Dei / rParsons, Susan Frank -- tTrinity, Marriage, and Homosexuality / rRogers, Eugene F. -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe opponents of legal recognition for same-sex marriage frequently appeal to a "Judeo-Christian" tradition. But does it make any sense to speak of that tradition as a single teaching on marriage? Are there elements in Jewish and Christian traditions that actually authorize religious and civil recognition of same-sex couples? And are contemporary heterosexual marriages well supported by those traditions? As evidenced by the ten provocative essays assembled and edited by Mark D. Jordan, the answers are not as simple as many would believe. The scholars of Judaism and Christianity gathered here explore the issue through a wide range of biblical, historical, liturgical, and theological evidence. From David's love for Jonathan through the singleness of Jesus and Paul to the all-male heaven of John's Apocalypse, the collection addresses pertinent passages in the Hebrew Bible and the New Testament with scholarly precision. It reconsiders whether there are biblical precedents for blessing same-sex unions in Jewish and Christian liturgies. The book concludes by analyzing typical religious arguments against such unions and provides a comprehensive response to claims that the Judeo-Christian tradition prohibits same-sex unions from receiving religious recognition. The essays, most of which are in print here for the first time, are by Saul M. Olyan, Mary Ann Tolbert, Daniel Boyarin, Laurence Paul Hemming, Steven Greenberg, Kathryn Tanner, Susan Frank Parsons, Eugene F. Rogers, Jr., and Mark D. Jordan.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 7aRELIGION / Sexuality & Gender Studies.2bisacsh1 aJordan, Mark D., eeditor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066258008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton Univ. Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311041343408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311045953140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400827138423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400827138.jpg  a978-3-11-041343-4  Princeton Univ. Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton eBook Package Backlist 2000